eurodist.mds <- cmdscale(eurodist)  # k=2 by default
  1. Plot these coordinates and label them with the city names. Does your plot look like the map of Europe?
Solution 
plot(eurodist.mds)
text(eurodist.mds, labels = row.names(eurodist.mds))

This has put labels on top of each other making it difficult to read. We can use ggplot2 and the ggrepel package to create a more elegant plot, but first we have to create a data frame.

library(ggplot2)
library(ggrepel)
coords = data.frame(x=eurodist.mds[,1], y=eurodist.mds[,2])

ggplot(coords, aes(x=x, y=y)) +
    geom_point() +
  geom_text_repel(aes(label = row.names(eurodist.mds)), size = 3)

This is upside down, so let’s multiply the y-axis by -1.

coords = data.frame(x=eurodist.mds[,1], y=-1*eurodist.mds[,2])
ggplot(coords, aes(x=x, y=y)) +
    geom_point() +
  geom_text_repel(aes(label = row.names(eurodist.mds)), size = 3)

#plot(tmp, cex=0)

The rotation is still a little off but we can see that most of the cities are roughly in the right place.

So there are significant negative eigenvalues for the distance matrix. This is because the distances are distance by road, not Euclidean distance. Over the scale of the continent, the Earth’s curvature would also have a small effect.

  1. Create the Euclidean distance matrix from your set of 2-dimensional points. What is the Frobenius norm between this matrix and the original distance matrix? Use cmdscale to create a set of points in 3 dimensional space and recompute the distance matrix.
Solution

The Frobenius norm of a matrix is the square root of the sum of the elements squared. We only have a lower diagonal matrix, and so we need to multiply the sum by 2.

dist1 <- dist(eurodist.mds)
dist2 <- dist(cmdscale(eurodist, k=3), diag=TRUE, upper = TRUE) 
sqrt(sum((eurodist-dist1)^2)*2)
[1] 3236.514
sqrt(sum((eurodist-dist2)^2)*2)# use 3 dimensions
[1] 3202.471

So using 3 components has slightly reduced the error, but not by much.

  1. Perform classical MDS for both similarity matrices, producing a plot of the coordinates (in 2d). Are the results similar?
Solution 
FtoD <- function(FF){
  n = dim(FF)[1]
  D <- matrix(nr=n,nc=n)
  for(ii in 1:n){
    for(jj in 1:n){
      D[ii,jj] <- sqrt(FF[ii,ii]+FF[jj,jj]-2*FF[ii,jj])
    }
  }
  return(D)
}

mds_Jacc <- cmdscale(FtoD(F_Jacc))
mds_SMC <- cmdscale(FtoD(F_SMC))

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
plot(mds_Jacc,cex=0, main="Jaccard similarity")
text(mds_Jacc,label=1:11)
plot(mds_SMC,cex=0, main="SMC similarity")
text(mds_SMC,label=1:11)

The results look quite different, and so in this case, analysis based on the Jaccard index would differ significantly to analysis based on the SMC.

Task 3

In this question we will look at data from 1888 on the fertility and socio-economic status of 47 French speaking provinces in Switzerland.

  1. Compute the Euclidean distance matrix for these data.
Solution 
data(swiss)
dist(swiss)
  1. Use MDS to create a 2-dimensional representation of the data and plot these points, labelling them with the province name.
Solution 
library(dplyr)
library(ggpubr) # repels figure labels
# Compute MDS
mds <- swiss |>  dist() |>          
  cmdscale() |> data.frame()
colnames(mds) <- c("x", "y")

ggplot(mds, aes(x=x, y=y)) +
    geom_point() +
  geom_text_repel(aes(label = row.names(swiss)), size = 3)

  1. Use MDS to create a 3-dimensional representation of the data.
Solution 
mds3 <- swiss |>
  dist() |>          
  cmdscale(k=3) |> data.frame()

library(rgl)
plot3d(mds3)

plot3d should create a pop-up window that you can then manually rotate.

  1. MDS can be also used to reveal a hidden pattern in a correlation matrix. Find the correlation matrix, \(\mathbf R\), of the swiss data. Perform MDS using \(1-\mathbf R\) as the distance matrix and plot the results. Positively correlated covariates are close together on the same side of the plot.
Solution 
D=1-cor(swiss)
mdsR <- D |> cmdscale() |> data.frame()
colnames(mdsR) <- c("Dim.1", "Dim.2")
# Plot MDS
ggscatter(mdsR, x = "Dim.1", y = "Dim.2", 
          label=colnames(swiss),
          size = 1,
          repel = TRUE)

Task 4

Try MDS on the MNIST data but looking for a 3d representation. Colour the points by their digit label, and create some interactive 3d plots. Does this find useful structure in the data? And is it more informative than the 2d plots we created in the notes.

Solution 
load('../Notes_bookdown/Bookdown/mnist.rda')
X<- mnist$train$x[1:1000,] # select juist the first 1000 images
Digits <- mnist$train$y[1:1000]
Y<- (X>0.3)*1.  # convert intensities to binary
# multiply by 1 to convert from T/F to a 1/0

n=dim(Y)[1]
p=dim(Y)[2]

F_SMC=(p-as.matrix(dist(Y, method="manhattan", diag = TRUE, upper = TRUE)))/p
F_Jaccard = 1-as.matrix(dist(Y, method="binary", diag=TRUE, upper=TRUE))

mds1=data.frame(cmdscale(FtoD(F_SMC), k = 3))
mds2=data.frame(cmdscale(FtoD(F_Jaccard), k = 3))

The rgl package creates interactive plots you can manipulate.

library(rgl)
plot3d(mds1, col=Digits+1)
plot3d(mds2, col=Digits+1)

The plotly package creates interactive plots. Try the following:

library(plotly)

mds1$digit <- as.factor(Digits) 
# so that we get a discrete colour scheme

fig <- plot_ly(mds1, x = ~X1, y = ~X2, z = ~X3, color = ~digit)#, colors = c('#BF382A', '#0C4B8E'))
fig <- fig |> add_markers(size=5)
fig


mds2$digit <- as.factor(Digits) 
# so that we get a discrete colour scheme

fig2 <- plot_ly(mds2, x = ~X1, y = ~X2, z = ~X3, color = ~digit)#, colors = c('#BF382A', '#0C4B8E'))
fig2 <- fig2 |> add_markers(size=5)
fig2

Read the description of more advanced methods here. Pick one and find an R package that implements it and try it on the MNIST data.
